[1] Australia (Queensland)
Date: 6 Mar 2005
From: ProMED <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Queensland Government Health Information, Australia, 4 Mar 2005
[edited]


Dengue in Far North Queensland
------------------------------
Outbreak location
Thursday Island in the Torres Strait (about 1000km north of Cairns).
Date outbreak declared
2 March 2005
Number of cases
One confirmed case and 11 suspected cases.
Type of dengue
Dengue type 4
Maps illustrating the Dengue Warning Areas
Note: These maps illustrate the Dengue Warning Areas where dengue has
occurred within the last month
Thursday Island, Torres Strait Islands
Advice
Torres Strait and Northern Peninsula Area residents are urged to take
immediate steps to prevent dengue fever.
Queensland Health�s Tropical Public Health Unit says the outbreak of dengue
type 4 poses a serious health risk to anyone in the Torres who has had dengue
before. Anyone who acquires dengue more than once is at risk of developing
dengue haemorrhagic fever, which can be fatal.
To protect yourself from dengue fever, you should:
- get rid of mosquito breeding sites in homes and yards, especially pot plant
bases, tyres, and buckets used for striking plant cuttings
- use insect repellent � wear personal repellent during the day and
reapply it according to the label.
- use plug-in mosquito zappers,
- use cockroach surface spray under tables, chairs and beds in the
home.
Anyone who has any symptoms of dengue fever should see their health centre
immediately.
--
ProMED
<promed@promedmail.org>
[This is a model of the way official information on a disease outbreak
should be disseminated to the public on the web -- short and concise.
- Mod.JW]
