[2] Australia (Queensland)
Date: Sun, 6 Mar 2005 07:57:04 +0900 (JST)
From: ProMED <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: ABC Online 6 Mar 2006 [edited]
<http://www.abc.net.au/queensland/news/200503/s1316909.htm>

3 cases of type 4 dengue fever have been confirmed in the region and there
are at least 13 suspected cases. [The outbreak of type 2 dengue fever in
Townsville, north Australia, was officially declared over in the 1st week of
September 2004, after no new cases were reported for the previous 3 months;
see ref. (28) below. � Mod.JW]
3 Northern Territory government mosquito experts leave today to help a
Queensland health team contain the latest dengue fever outbreak in the Torres
Strait. 2 of them have practical experience with the mosquito eradication
team in Tennant Creek and one is a Darwin specialist in exotic insects.
The Department of Health's medical entomologist, Peter Whelan, says the first
week of their stay is the most important in the containment of the
outbreak. "Primarily that involves locating and treating anywhere where there
are these mosquitos and they're breeding," he said. "The most important
locations to tackle first are where the suspected cases and where the
confirmed cases are, that means that in that area will be probably infected
mosquitos."
Mr Whelan says it is very important to contain the outbreak on Thursday
Island as soon as possible. "First of all it's to stop the people on Thursday
Island from getting dengue," he said. �The other thing is that if these
people infected with the dengue virus travel to any of the other areas in
north Queensland or even into Tennant Creek, there's a chance
that they're taking the virus with them and then infect local mosquitos in
other towns like Cairns or Townsville."
--
ProMED
<promed@promedmail.org>
