[4] Yemen (Hodeidah)
Date: 26 Feb 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Yemen Observer
<http://www.yobserver.com/news_3936.php>

Dengue fever outbreak reported in Hodeidah
------------------------------------------
Primary medical reports revealed that more than 20 cases of dengue fever have
been discovered in the district of Hodeidah. The number of suspected cases
reached 34, but 4 cases turned out to be malarial infection. 30 were examined
in Sana'a and appeared to have caught dengue fever. The media at large
reported 300 deaths from the disease.
Majed Al-Jonaid, deputy minister of health, emphasizes that a number of
people died in one district of Hodeidah but no new cases of the fever have
been reported since 16 Jan 2005. 34 people thought to have been afflicted
with dengue fever were not serious, although one girl who was in critical
condition was subsequently treated and recovered.
Al-Jonaid said that the Ministry of Public Health & Population is carrying
out a campaign in cooperation with the WHO to observe and control the disease
in Hodeidah and that this project will be extended to include all
governorates. In addition, the ministry will provide free medical services
and distribute protective mosquito nets to prevent further cases. He said
that awareness campaigns would form 90 percent of the battle to combat the
disease. Al-Jonaid said that local radio stations and the health campaign
vehicles with megaphones are carrying out the task. He also said that filling
up areas of mosquito proliferation with soil is one important method of
fighting the disease
Al-Jonaid indicated that it was not the first time this epidemic has occurred
in Yemen. Dengue fever appeared in Shabwa in November 2002 and in neighboring
countries such as Saudi Arabia and Ethiopia. Saudi Arabia announced cases of
the disease a month ago.
Dr. Hashim Al-Zein, representative of the WHO in Yemen, told the press most
of the suspected cases occurred in Hodeidah. It was prevalent in individuals
but not in groups. A WHO-assigned team is continuing its search for the
remaining cases as well as observing and controlling the proliferation of the
disease and the insects that carry it in areas where they have been found.
--
ProMED
<promed@promedmail.org>
