[5] Malaysia
Date: Feb 24, 2005
From: Alfonso Rodriguez, M.D.<ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: Bernama.com news, Malaysia [edited]
<http://www.bernama.com/bernama/v3/news_lite.php?id=120787>
2 people died of dengue this month [Bebruary 2005] making the total number
of deaths due to the outbreak this year to 24 nationwide. Health Ministry's
Disease Control Division Director Dr Ramlee Rahmat said a 21-year-old man
died at Melaka Hospital on 6 Feb 2005 while the other was a 54-year-old-man
at Selayang Hospital on 16 Feb 2005. Speaking at the weekly press conference
on the dengue outbreak, here Thursday, he said the number of dengue cases
reported in the 7th week of this year rose by 124 to 1087 cases compared to
963 cases in the previous week. However, 4 states recorded lower dengue
cases: Negeri Sembilan, Sabah, Pahang & Labuan , he said. Selangor remained
as the state with the highest number of dengue cases with 427, followed by
Kuala Lumpur (172), Perak (125), Penang (63) and Johor (43).
Dr Ramlee said to control the outbreak, Health Departments in the states had
been directed to intensify continuous control and prevention efforts
especially in the states which recorded an increase in the dengue cases. He
also called on property developers to play a role in the efforts as the
number of construction sites found breeding mosquitoes was still high. In
Selangor alone, he said, out of 101 construction sites inspected in the 7th
week of the year, 69 were found breeding mosquitoes while in Kuala Lumpur, 27
of 34 construction sites were found breeding mosquitoes. He said the Health
Ministry had issued compound fines to 422 premises and ordered one premises
to close down.
--
Alfonso Rodriguez, M.D.
<ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
*****
[6] Brazil (Rondonia)
Date: 2 Mar 2005
From: Promed-Port@promedmail.org
Source: Folha On Line 1 Mar 2005 [in Portuguese, summarized by JW]
<http://www1.folha.uol.com.br>
3 people died of dengue in Ariquemes, a municipality (pop. 86 900) in the
metropolitan area of the capital, Porto Velho, of the western Brazil state
of Rondonia [bordering Bolivia] in February 2005; 2 had dengue but died of
complications, the 3rd, a 38-year-old woman, had DHF. Of the 12 states which
notify dengue cases to the Ministry of Health, Rondonia has the worst
situation, with 3141 notified cases of classic dengue and 2 of confirmed DHF,
more than triple the number for the 1st 2 months of 2004, when 1029 cases
were notified -- and 5319 for the whole year 2004. In 2004, one person died
of dengue (not DHF) in Porto Velho, where there have only been 138 cases of
dengue this year [2005].
According to the city director of public health, Leila Boff, 12 Family Health
Program teams & 130 community health agents are actively combating the
disease in Ariquemes.
--
